      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_422597_1828-02_page01.jpg"/>
            <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
            <opener>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Black-Castle_IE">Black Castle near<lb/>
                  <hi rend="underline">Navan</hi>
                  <lb/>
               </placeName>
               <salute>
                  <persName>
                     <!-- Use if letter has a saluation ("Dear Sir," for example). If not, delete this line.-->
                     My dear Sir
                  </persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>It is impossible that any<lb/>
               black marks I can make<lb/>
               upon paper can convey to<lb/>
               you the idea of the concern<lb/>
               I feel for these changes —<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>It is not for you or for <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LansH1">Lord Lansdowne</persName>
               <lb/>
               Lansdowne that I feel but
               for <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName> — the loss of place<lb/>
               and power may for aught<lb/>
               I know may be again of <choice>
                  <orig>happi-<lb/>
               ness</orig>
                  <reg>happiness</reg>
               </choice> to you both — But the<lb/>
               loss to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName> of such friends<lb/>
               in power is I fear <choice>
                  <orig>irremedia<lb/>
               'ble</orig>
                  <reg>irremediable</reg>
               </choice> —<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I have much that I wish<lb/>
               to say to you, which I cannot<lb/>
               &amp; ought not to put on paper<lb/>
               — for instance - circumstances<lb/>
               I have privately learned from<lb/>
               catholics respecting late distur<choice>
                  <orig>
                     <lb/>
                     <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_422597_1828-02_page02.jpg"/>
               bances</orig>
                  <reg>disturbances</reg>
               </choice> in this Town of <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Navan_IE">Navan</placeName>
               <lb/>
               — and elsewhere —<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>The hand of despotism<lb/>
               may press down &amp; <hi rend="underline">keep</hi>down<lb/>
               a nation if that hand be strong<lb/>
               enough — But the hand must<lb/>
               <del>be</del> in that case <hi rend="underline">never be removed</hi>
               <lb/>
               &amp; must never relax —<lb/>
               To the conqueror of Waterloo<lb/>
               The <hi rend="underline">recon</hi>quest of <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName> would<lb/>
               appear &amp; be easy perhaps; &amp; there<lb/>
               fore his mil<hi rend="superscript">n</hi> genius may brave<lb/>
               &amp; despise the danger of putting<lb/>
               things to this issue — But — after<lb/>
               wards — he must be prepared<lb/>
               to exterminate - he can<lb/>
               no otherwise extinguish <add>public</add>opinion<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CromO1">Cromwell</persName>— who was better<lb/>
               made for the purpose than<lb/>
               any other man stopped short<lb/>
               of the mark &amp; after wading<lb/>
               through slaughter to his<lb/>
               church left 50,000 to tell<lb/>
               the tale —<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>But I have no business with<lb/>
               these things --<lb/>
               NB. I do not think from what I have<lb/>
               heard that the priests would dare<lb/>
               to let themselves be paid by Govt<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_422597_1828-02_page03.jpg"/>
               unless <hi rend="underline">Cat - eman</hi>. were same time granted<lb/>
               — Great debating may be upon the means<lb/>
               &amp; tenets of said words — we shall hear from<lb/>
               the Pope I suppose soon — &amp; from you? — When?<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>You were so very kind to<lb/>
               my brother <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">William</persName>— another<lb/>
               brother of mine — <hi rend="underline">
                  <persName type="person" ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeC1">Sneyd</persName>
               </hi>E —<lb/>
               now begs me to recal him<lb/> 
               to your memory — These are<lb/>
               his words<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>"Now that<persName ref="./Personography.xml#SpriT1">Spring Rice</persName> is not in<lb/>
               "office can you <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Maria give me</persName>
               <lb/>
               "a pretext for calling on him —<lb/>
               "I should like much to renew my<lb/>
               "acquaintance with one whom<lb/>
               "I foresaw would be a distinguished<lb/>
               "man when I met him at <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SmedE1">Edward<lb/>
               "Smedley's</persName> chambers at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Trinity-College_IE">Trinity</placeName>"<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>It will gratify me and<lb/>
               my brother much if you can<lb/>
               give him half an hour of<lb/>
               your conversation — I enclose<lb/>
               a note for him — Send it by<lb/>
               2<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> post. It contains a little note<lb/>
               of introduction for him to you<lb/>
               which is all I can do for him<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>He is a more literary man<lb/>
               than <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">William</persName> &amp; having seen<lb/>
               a great deal of the world<lb/>
               abroad for many years has<lb/>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_422597_1828-02_page04.jpg"/>
               more that will make half an<lb/>
               hour's conversation agreeable<lb/>
               to you — Oblige me — and I shall<lb/>
               be obliged — which is more than<lb/>
               many people who ask favors<lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">can promise</hi> or at least more<lb/>
               than they are often found to per<lb/>
               form<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
            I am Yours very sincerely<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
               <date>Feb 8<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1828</date>
            </closer>
            <postscript>
               <p><!--A postscript goes here, outside the <closer>. --></p>
